\begin_layout Paragraph*
Capacitance meter IN1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capacitance connected between IN1 and Ground can be measured.
 It works better for lower capacitance values, upto 10 nanoFarads, results
 may not be very accurate beyond that.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Frequency Counter IN2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capable of measuring frequencies upto several MHz.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Resistive Sensor Input (SEN):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is mainly meant for sensors like Light Dependent Resistor, Thermistor,
 Photo-transistor etc.
 SEN is internally connected to 3.3 volts through a 
\begin_inset Formula $5.1k\Omega$
\end_inset

 resistor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Formula $\pm16V$
\end_inset

 Analog Inputs, A1 & A2: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can measure voltage within the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm16$
\end_inset

 volts range.
 The input voltage range can be selected from .5V to 16V fullscale.
 Voltage at these terminals can be displayed as a function of time, giving
 the functionality of a low frequency oscilloscope.
 The maximum sampling rate is 1 Msps /channel.
 Both have an input impedance of 
\begin_inset Formula $1M\Omega$
\end_inset

